	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1246630" style="border-right: 1px solid #D1D1E1">
	
		
		

		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1246630"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				I'd submit that if someone's principles aren't worth dying for, then those principles are also not worth living for and should just be abandoned for something better.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>I&#8217;d submit that she has the priority of her principles screwed up.  Keeping it abstract makes her appear noble, considering all of the principles makes her appear to have poor judgment.  So let&#8217;s break it down:<br />
<br />
Principle X:  A mother has an obligation to care for her children<br />
Principle Y:  G-d told me not to have a blood transfusion.  <br />
<br />
What we have here are two principles in opposition to one another.  If she is willing to die for Principle Y then she has violated Principle X, and vice versa.  It must therefore be the case that she has Placed Principle Y above Principle X, IOW, in her judgment, Religion is greater than Family.  <br />
<br />
I would not formulate the dilemma as &#8220;Do you have something that you&#8217;d give up YOUR life for,&#8221; I&#8217;d formulate it as follows:  Do you have a principle that would cause you to intentionally turn your children into orphans?  For clarification, knowledge that refusing a blood transfusion would almost certainly kill you is Intent.  <br />
<br />
Mature religions deal with dilemmas like this, granting exceptions for special cases.  An Orthodox Jew is going to be able to eat bacon if he&#8217;s stranded on a desert Island and its his only food, a Muslim is not going to hell if he&#8217;s locked in a cell and his captors won&#8217;t let him pray, etc.  My goodness people, whatever you believe in gave you a brain because it expected us to use it.  <br />
<br />
If G-d wants people to die by refusing blood transfusions, then there are only two possibilities:<br />
<br />
1.	G-d is an asshole, unworthy of our worship; or<br />
2.	You interpreted the bible wrong.   <br />
<br />
There is no third possibility.  Don&#8217;t be a stupid head and expect that saying G-d told me to be a stupid head should be a shield from criticism.    <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				I'm curious to know what principles someone would give up their life for?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>My life is cheap; my children&#8217;s lives are priceless.  If such a principle exists, it&#8217;s certainly not one based on an interpretation of ambiguous text written down in a Holy Book.  I&#8217;d like to think I&#8217;d give my life up to protect an innocent from murder or rape.  Since G-d, or whoever, gave me a brain, I rank saving innocents as a higher Principle than &#8220;I suck at reading comprehension and think G-d told me not to have blood transfusions.&#8221;   <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				How about just accepting that someone else is entitled to believe as they want, and us not judge them based on our own beliefs?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>How about accepting that someone is entitled to what they believe and then ridiculing them for being dumb asses, lest other people too act like dumb asses.  <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				The easiest explanation would be you're required to respect 'stupid and cruel' beliefs because the protection of the First Amendment is as much about freedom to practice as it is anti-establishment. It's easy to throw a label on someone and demand that their religious beliefs not be respected, but I bet you'd have a problem if someone tried to use the government to force their religion on you, right?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>My goodness people, the First Amendment is sacrosanct, it means we have to tolerate other people&#8217;s religious beliefs, it doesn&#8217;t mean that we have to accept or respect them.  If you want someone to fight for your right to believe and practice your religion, then I'm your ally.   If you want someone who will shut down their mind and unquestionably parrot the mindless notion that we should respect stupidity so long as someone believes their G-d/Mother-goddess/FSM/Ceiling Cat told them to act stupid, then look elsewhere.  <br />
<br />
I judge ACTIONS though, and BELIEFS only to the extent that those beliefs result in BAD ACTIONS.  Refusing life saving medical treatment and robbing your kids of their mother is a BAD ACTION, and should thus be judged poorly.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		
