		<div id="post_message_1247733"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Maurley</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">This is actually an interesting story because there are some Jews that state that Abraham failed this test.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Definately a gripping story and could be interpreted a number of ways.  But how someone could say that he failed after God's words to him after ... I don't see it.  Well, I have a theory, but I'm curious as to the actual rationale.<br />
<br />
Seems pretty clear to me, both from a cultural perspective and from the circumstances, that Abraham was doing it with the understanding that there would be no resurrection.  Heck, resurrection was unheard of to the culture at the time and, I may be mistaken in this, but they had no concept of heaven, right? <br />
<br />
Anyway, its not a unique concept in the bible.  Obedience (not to man, I might point out) is a number one priority.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

